<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <h1>Divorce Settlement Guides</h1>
  <p>Plain-language guides written and reviewed by editorial staff with experience in family law and divorce litigation. Each guide provides the practical and legal context behind divorce settlement — what the law requires, what courts consider, and what choices you face at each stage of the process.</p>

  <h2><a href="/guides/how-divorce-asset-division-works/">How Divorce Asset Division Works</a></h2>
  <p>The mechanics of property classification and division: the difference between marital and separate property, how community property and equitable distribution regimes operate, how retirement accounts are divided, how real estate is handled, and what factors courts weigh in equitable distribution states. The foundational guide for understanding what is at stake financially in a divorce.</p>

  <h2><a href="/guides/spousal-support-guide/">Spousal Support Guide</a></h2>
  <p>A comprehensive look at alimony: the different types of spousal support (temporary, rehabilitative, permanent, reimbursement), how courts calculate amounts, how duration is determined, the post-2018 tax treatment change, and the rules for modification and termination. Includes how cohabitation affects ongoing support obligations.</p>

  <h2><a href="/guides/what-to-do-during-divorce/">What to Do During Divorce</a></h2>
  <p>Practical financial and legal steps for protecting yourself during a divorce proceeding: gathering and preserving financial documents, avoiding dissipation of marital assets, understanding temporary orders, opening individual accounts, and working effectively with a family law attorney. Covers what to do in the first weeks after separation.</p>

  <h2><a href="/guides/divorce-settlement-misconceptions/">Common Divorce Settlement Misconceptions</a></h2>
  <p>Five widely held misunderstandings about divorce: that everything splits 50/50, that adultery produces financial advantages, that retirement accounts are protected, that alimony is permanent, and that moving out of the marital home forfeits property rights. Each misconception is examined against how family law actually operates.</p>

